<br>
Even the American Revolution was a war fought over money.  Remember &quot;taxation without representation&quot;?  Sure, a secondary benefit of the war was our freedom, but colonists who opposed the revolution felt we should have fought harder to simply have representation back in Mother England.  But the colonists who realized that the King would never allow the colonies to have representation knew that the only answer was war - a war to separate the Colonies from England.<br>
<br>
So now, more than 200 years later, we're off to fight a war in Iraq.  And sure, there are monetary reasons involved.  Same as there are monetary reasons behind the opposition from France and Russia.  But the secondary benefits you mentioned: removing Saddam's arsenal of WMD and the freedom of his people... those are worthy causes.  If we as a nation (the United States) somehow benefit monetarily in the process of disarming and overthrowing Saddam and freeing his people, then I don't necessarily see that as a bad thing.<br>
<br>
To use a tried cliche - money makes this world go 'round.  And to think that our nation, or ANY nation in the world opperates without that thought foremost in their minds is completely unrealistic. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><br>
